{
  "doc_id": "32615",
  "text": "Lee and colleagues [CITATION_1] found that under normal conditions, GLUT10 localized to Golgi in adipocytes, while insulin stimulated the translocation of the transporter into mitochondria. In mouse AVSMCs and rat A10 cells, GLUT10 was abundant in mitochondria, where it was shown to enhance DHA uptake. In H 2 O 2 -treated cells, DHA reduced the level of reactive oxygen species (ROS), protecting cells from ROS-induced vascular damage [CITATION_2] . Later it was shown that human HEK293 cells express a functional AA transporter that coincides sodium coupled ascorbic acid transporter (SVCT2), which questioned the importance of GLUT10-dependent mitochondrial AA uptake [CITATION_3] . In silico predictions disproved the role of GLUT10 in mitochondrial DHA transport, as the transporter achieved the lowest mitochondrial localization scores [CITATION_4] .",
